to lean towards your offer,
even if it's potentially even

00:19:35.720 --> 00:19:37.980
less, because it's
more secure offer.

00:19:37.980 --> 00:19:40.040
Conventional loans
are pretty much what

00:19:40.040 --> 00:19:42.600
you guys have probably
all bought your properties

00:19:42.600 --> 00:19:43.860
if you own house.

00:19:43.860 --> 00:19:48.160
A conventional loan, your
Wells Fargo, your Citibank,

00:19:48.160 --> 00:19:49.110
things like that.

00:19:49.110 --> 00:19:52.970
And conventional, you're
putting down 20% up

00:19:52.970 --> 00:19:55.687
to potentially 30%
on your property,

00:19:55.687 --> 00:19:57.270
and they're going
to finance the rest.

00:19:57.270 --> 00:19:59.105
So that's a conventional loan.

00:19:59.105 --> 00:20:01.730
BRANDON: All right, next I want
to talk about government loans.

00:20:01.730 --> 00:20:03.730
How many of you guys
actually own your own home?

00:20:03.730 --> 00:20:04.679
Can I ask that?

00:20:04.679 --> 00:20:05.470
Quite a few people.

00:20:05.470 --> 00:20:08.840
Did anybody use an FHA
loan when they did it?

00:20:08.840 --> 00:20:10.760
All right, so let me explain.

00:20:10.760 --> 00:20:13.702
FHA-- there's also VA
and USDA-- we're not

00:20:13.702 --> 00:20:16.160
going to do that-- FHA is a
loan program the government has

00:20:16.160 --> 00:20:20.080
which insures your loan, which
means you can get a cheaper

00:20:20.080 --> 00:20:21.630
down payment.

00:20:21.630 --> 00:20:23.190
Right now it's at 3.5%.

00:20:23.190 --> 00:20:25.650
So if you're buying a $100,000
property, which, I know,

00:20:25.650 --> 00:20:28.108
is cheap, but if you were buying
$100,000 for easy numbers,

00:20:28.108 --> 00:20:30.060
$3,500 is what you
would need down.

00:20:30.060 --> 00:20:32.540
Now granted, you have to
live in that property--

00:20:32.540 --> 00:20:33.720
I think it's for a year.

00:20:33.720 --> 00:20:36.504
But it could be a duplex,
triplex, or fourplex.

00:20:36.504 --> 00:20:38.670
My favorite strategy in all
of real estate investing

00:20:38.670 --> 00:20:41.327
is to find a multi-family
property like that,

00:20:41.327 --> 00:20:43.410
live in one of the units,
rent the other ones out.

00:20:43.410 --> 00:20:44.140
Move out later.

00:20:44.140 --> 00:20:46.310
And you've got that
nice fixed rate,

00:20:46.310 --> 00:20:49.221
low down payment multi-family
property that just provides

00:20:49.221 --> 00:20:50.720
cash flow for the
rest of your life.

00:20:50.720 --> 00:20:52.719
I did that actually with
a duplex that I bought.

00:20:52.719 --> 00:20:54.430
Ended it up,
interesting, it ended up

00:20:54.430 --> 00:20:55.930
that duplex we found
out years later

00:20:55.930 --> 00:20:59.761
was Kurt Cobain's very first
house, which is interesting.

00:20:59.761 --> 00:21:01.510
We found out because
some Swedish tourists

00:21:01.510 --> 00:21:04.350
were knocking on the door trying
to take pictures of the inside.

00:21:04.350 --> 00:21:04.850
Yeah.

00:21:04.850 --> 00:21:06.210
Fun side story.

00:21:06.210 --> 00:21:08.880
JOSH: And now he owns two
of Kurt Cobain's houses.

00:21:08.880 --> 00:21:09.530
It's true.

00:21:09.530 --> 00:21:11.894
If anyone wants one,
any Nirvana fans?

00:21:11.894 --> 00:21:12.935
Does anyone like Nirvana?

00:21:12.935 --> 00:21:14.550
There's an investment
house for sale.

00:21:14.550 --> 00:21:15.049
Anyone?

00:21:15.049 --> 00:21:16.150
Anyone?

00:21:16.150 --> 00:21:17.680
Bueller?

00:21:17.680 --> 00:21:18.770
All right.

00:21:18.770 --> 00:21:19.680
Portfolio loans.

00:21:19.680 --> 00:21:21.860
Portfolio loans
are loans that are

00:21:21.860 --> 00:21:24.430
owned by the lender themselves.

00:21:24.430 --> 00:21:26.859
So you guys remember the
housing crisis where everybody's

00:21:26.859 --> 00:21:29.150
talking about slicing and
dicing loans and selling them

00:21:29.150 --> 00:21:30.240
and things like that.

00:21:30.240 --> 00:21:34.370
Portfolio loans are where a
banking, a lending institution,

00:21:34.370 --> 00:21:36.170
is going to own the loan.

00:21:36.170 --> 00:21:37.580
They're not going
to sell it off.

00:21:37.580 --> 00:21:39.390
The nice thing about
portfolio lenders

00:21:39.390 --> 00:21:42.770
are they love
investors, and they're

00:21:42.770 --> 00:21:44.990
pretty easy to work
with, generally.

00:21:44.990 --> 00:21:46.901
If you've got good
deals, they want them.

00:21:46.901 --> 00:21:48.650
So they're going to
want to work with you.

00:21:48.650 --> 00:21:51.040
They're not gonna-- especially
if you start to learn how

00:21:51.040 --> 00:21:53.550
to deal with lenders, and
you can present yourself

00:21:53.550 --> 00:21:57.690
in a professional way, and give
them your loan package and say,

00:21:57.690 --> 00:22:00.430
hey, here's a property,
here's all the details,

00:22:00.430 --> 00:22:02.844
and you do well by it,
they're going to love you.

00:22:02.844 --> 00:22:04.760
They're going to want
you to keep coming back.

00:22:04.760 --> 00:22:08.090
And portfolio lenders are
definitely a preferred source

00:22:08.090 --> 00:22:11.689
of money for most
sophisticated investors.

00:22:11.689 --> 00:22:12.480
BRANDON: All right.

00:22:12.480 --> 00:22:13.820
The next type of loan
that's pretty popular

00:22:13.820 --> 00:22:14.730
is a commercial loan.

00:22:14.730 --> 00:22:16.870
If you're gonna buy a property
like a large multi-family

00:22:16.870 --> 00:22:18.411
five units and up,
or if you're going

00:22:18.411 --> 00:22:20.934
to buy an office building,
trailer park, whatever,

00:22:20.934 --> 00:22:22.850
you're going to want to
use a commercial loan.

00:22:22.850 --> 00:22:25.369
They're very similar to
portfolio in that any bank can

00:22:25.369 --> 00:22:26.660
generally do a commercial loan.

00:22:26.660 --> 00:22:29.201
They usually require a little
bit higher down payment-- maybe

00:22:29.201 --> 00:22:30.750
25%, 30%.

00:22:30.750 --> 00:22:32.610
But it can finance--
I mean, if you can--

00:22:32.610 --> 00:22:34.610
Here's a cool example of
something you could do.

00:22:34.610 --> 00:22:37.570
Let's say you get 10 guys
together, all throw in $50,000.

00:22:37.570 --> 00:22:38.871
You've got $500,000.

00:22:38.871 --> 00:22:40.620
You go to a bank and
get a commercial loan

00:22:40.620 --> 00:22:42.990
on a $10 million property.

00:22:42.990 --> 00:22:45.090
Use the 10 guys you
gathered together

00:22:45.090 --> 00:22:47.380
as a down payment on the
commercial loan and the rest.

00:22:47.380 --> 00:22:48.485
There's a lot of
fun games you can

00:22:48.485 --> 00:22:50.340
play with that when
you go commercial.

00:22:50.340 --> 00:22:52.550
So if you guys decide
to go commercial,

00:22:52.550 --> 00:22:56.005
yeah, look into that and find
a good commercial lender.

00:22:56.005 --> 00:22:58.865
JOSH: And find a good
real estate attorney.

00:22:58.865 --> 00:23:01.240
Don't just like, hey, we're
going to throw money together

00:23:01.240 --> 00:23:02.240
and we're gonna do this!

00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:04.980
Like you want to, again,
about the education.

00:23:04.980 --> 00:23:07.140
I know Brandon uses it,
and it's a good example,

00:23:07.140 --> 00:23:10.870
but truth be told, don't
go out there and do stuff

00:23:10.870 --> 00:23:13.035
unless you've made
sure that it's legit

00:23:13.035 --> 00:23:15.986
and it's kosher, because there's
a lot of bad information--

00:23:15.986 --> 00:23:17.610
I'm not saying his
information is bad--

00:23:17.610 --> 00:23:19.568
but there's a lot of bad
information out there,

00:23:19.568 --> 00:23:22.180
and you really do have
to be careful of that.

00:23:22.180 --> 00:23:25.620
So I really do recommend--
and we don't talk about team

00:23:25.620 --> 00:23:28.670
at all on this, but part
of your investing team

00:23:28.670 --> 00:23:30.540
absolutely should be a
real estate attorney.

00:23:30.540 --> 00:23:32.350
It's one most important people.

00:23:32.350 --> 00:23:35.140
[RANDOM AUDIO OUTBURST]

00:23:35.140 --> 00:23:36.690
JOSH: And thank you very much.

00:23:36.690 --> 00:23:38.600
All right so we've got
hard money lenders.

00:23:38.600 --> 00:23:42.069
Hard money lenders are
kind of the loan sharks.

00:23:42.069 --> 00:23:43.860
A lot of people think--
if you hear of them

00:23:43.860 --> 00:23:45.276
and they think
loan sharks, right?

00:23:45.276 --> 00:23:48.820
These are guys who actually
loan money for short term--

00:23:48.820 --> 00:23:49.944
and it's pretty expensive.

00:23:49.944 --> 00:23:52.110
They're going to-- you're
going to pay points on it.

00:23:52.110 --> 00:23:55.371
You might be paying 12%,
15% on a hard money loan.

00:23:55.371 --> 00:23:57.370
But it's going to be a
loan for six months, nine

00:23:57.370 --> 00:23:58.580
months, something like that.

00:23:58.580 --> 00:24:01.390
This is one of the preferred
loans for flippers.

00:24:01.390 --> 00:24:03.680
House flippers love
hard money loans,

00:24:03.680 --> 00:24:05.749
because they're generally,
the hard-money lenders

00:24:05.749 --> 00:24:07.790
have an understanding of
what flippers are doing.

00:24:07.790 --> 00:24:09.248
They can look at
a property and say

00:24:09.248 --> 00:24:11.310
this is going to be a good deal.

00:24:11.310 --> 00:24:13.060
You're going to be
able turn it over fast.

00:24:13.060 --> 00:24:13.720
You have the resources.

00:24:13.720 --> 00:24:15.730
I'm going to give you the
money, make my money fast,

00:24:15.730 --> 00:24:17.063
and we're all going to be happy.

00:24:17.063 --> 00:24:19.109
Hard money loans.

00:24:19.109 --> 00:24:20.650
BRANDON: All right,
we're almost done

00:24:20.650 --> 00:24:21.370
with the different
financing things.

00:24:21.370 --> 00:24:23.260
But there's also
private money, which

00:24:23.260 --> 00:24:25.570
would be things like
family, or friends.

00:24:25.570 --> 00:24:28.316
If you borrow money from
somebody that you know,

00:24:28.316 --> 00:24:29.964
dangerous to do that.

00:24:29.964 --> 00:24:31.630
Not necessarily that
you know like well,

00:24:31.630 --> 00:24:34.924
but if you borrow money from
people that you might network

00:24:34.924 --> 00:24:36.340
with, that's called
private money.

00:24:36.340 --> 00:24:38.106
Usually a little bit cheaper.

00:24:38.106 --> 00:24:39.480
For example,
there's a guy I know

00:24:39.480 --> 00:24:41.749
in Portland who just lent
me $100,000 to go buy

00:24:41.749 --> 00:24:44.040
an investment property and
then I'm gonna refinance it.

00:24:44.040 --> 00:24:46.539
Worked out really great for me,
it worked out great for him,

00:24:46.539 --> 00:24:50.130
and that's a perfect
private money deal.

00:24:50.130 --> 00:24:52.970
So I recommend looking into that
if you're looking for financing

00:24:52.970 --> 00:24:55.320
and can't get it from a bank.

00:24:55.320 --> 00:24:57.830
JOSH: So that was private money.

00:24:57.830 --> 00:25:00.750
Partners-- and on
private money, you

00:25:00.750 --> 00:25:02.760
want to be really
sure the person you're

00:25:02.760 --> 00:25:04.680
working with-- you
are in bed with them.

00:25:04.680 --> 00:25:07.332
So make sure you're
comfortable with the folks

00:25:07.332 --> 00:25:08.290
that you're doing that.

00:25:08.290 --> 00:25:10.680
The same goes for partners.

00:25:10.680 --> 00:25:14.115
So partners would be, you know,
you and your buddy say hey,

00:25:14.115 --> 00:25:15.460
we want to get into the game.

00:25:15.460 --> 00:25:17.630
I'm going to put up
50%, and you put up 50%,

00:25:17.630 --> 00:25:19.480
and let's get in
this deal together.

00:25:19.480 --> 00:25:23.070
Or he may put up all the
money, you may do all the work,

00:25:23.070 --> 00:25:23.900
things like that.

00:25:23.900 --> 00:25:26.920
But if you work with folks, you
can come up with creative ways

00:25:26.920 --> 00:25:29.200
to potentially even do
deals with no cash out

00:25:29.200 --> 00:25:30.489
of your own pocket.

00:25:30.489 --> 00:25:33.030
But again, you want to make sure
you're very careful with who

00:25:33.030 --> 00:25:36.149
you're working with
which leads us to--

00:25:36.149 --> 00:25:36.940
BRANDON: All right.

00:25:36.940 --> 00:25:38.460
The last one I want to
talk about real quick

00:25:38.460 --> 00:25:39.620
is just seller financing.

00:25:39.620 --> 00:25:42.080
What seller financing is
is when you buy a property

00:25:42.080 --> 00:25:44.150
from the person who owns
it, and they actually

00:25:44.150 --> 00:25:45.677
carry the mortgage.

00:25:45.677 --> 00:25:47.510
So instead of you paying
a bank every month,

00:25:47.510 --> 00:25:48.801
you pay the seller every month.

00:25:48.801 --> 00:25:51.380
That's actually how I bought
my 24 unit apartment building.

00:25:51.380 --> 00:25:53.190
There was an older couple
who went to my church.

00:25:53.190 --> 00:25:54.712
I mentioned one
day, hey, you know,

00:25:54.712 --> 00:25:56.295
I'd love to buy an
apartment building.

00:25:56.295 --> 00:25:57.650
And they said, huh, interesting.

00:25:57.650 --> 00:25:58.760
We actually have one.

00:25:58.760 --> 00:26:00.020
And it worked out perfect.

00:26:00.020 --> 00:26:01.970
That's that networking thing
we talked about earlier.

00:26:01.970 --> 00:26:03.220
Well, what we ended
up doing is they

00:26:03.220 --> 00:26:04.762
ended up carrying
the contract on it,

00:26:04.762 --> 00:26:06.219
which is they
carried the mortgage.

00:26:06.219 --> 00:26:07.210
I pay them every month.

00:26:07.210 --> 00:26:09.084
They're this cute old
couple who drive around

00:26:09.084 --> 00:26:10.660
the country in their
motor home now.

00:26:10.660 --> 00:26:12.326
And like, that's their
entire retirement

00:26:12.326 --> 00:26:13.650
is what I pay them every month.

00:26:13.650 --> 00:26:14.900
It works out amazing for them.

00:26:14.900 --> 00:26:16.280
Worked out great for me.

00:26:16.280 --> 00:26:19.035
And it's a really,
really great way

00:26:19.035 --> 00:26:20.535
to buy real estate
if you can do it.

00:26:20.535 --> 00:26:21.936
JOSH: It's like an annuity.

00:26:21.936 --> 00:26:24.287
BRANDON: Yeah, yeah
it's really nice.

00:26:24.287 --> 00:26:26.120
With that, let's move
on to step number six.

00:26:26.120 --> 00:26:27.040
JOSH: All right.

00:26:27.040 --> 00:26:28.460
Step number six--
self management

00:26:28.460 --> 00:26:30.250
versus property management.

00:26:30.250 --> 00:26:32.700
We're not really talking about
flipping houses here, now.

00:26:32.700 --> 00:26:34.720
We're talking about
investment properties,

00:26:34.720 --> 00:26:38.180
buy and hold things--
buy and hold properties.

00:26:38.180 --> 00:26:40.360
So self managing
is pretty obvious.

00:26:40.360 --> 00:26:42.700
You buy a property, you're
taking care of the toilets,

00:26:42.700 --> 00:26:43.830
you're taking care
of the tenants,

00:26:43.830 --> 00:26:44.990
you're taking care
of the maintenance,

00:26:44.990 --> 00:26:46.490
you're taking care
of the headaches,

00:26:46.490 --> 00:26:49.430
and yes, you will
deal with all of that.

00:26:49.430 --> 00:26:52.950
Self managing is-- it
can be very challenging.

00:26:52.950 --> 00:26:54.560
It could be very fulfilling.

00:26:54.560 --> 00:26:57.260
In the end, it could
be very time-consuming.

00:26:57.260 --> 00:27:00.220
That said, if you're
going to become a landlord

00:27:00.220 --> 00:27:03.170
and end up having
somebody outside do it

00:27:03.170 --> 00:27:06.110
for you, definitely, definitely
recommend self managing

00:27:06.110 --> 00:27:08.520
first versus
property management.

00:27:08.520 --> 00:27:10.649
Property management, you're
gonna hire a company,

00:27:10.649 --> 00:27:12.440
they're going to take
care of the property.

00:27:12.440 --> 00:27:15.780
Now that said, when I told
you that I had a hard time

00:27:15.780 --> 00:27:16.780
and lost a lot of money.

00:27:16.780 --> 00:27:19.080
Well, I did that
primarily because I

00:27:19.080 --> 00:27:21.470
hired the wrong
property management.

00:27:21.470 --> 00:27:22.250
I went out there.

00:27:22.250 --> 00:27:23.791
I didn't know what
I was looking for.

00:27:23.791 --> 00:27:25.222
I didn't know what to do.

00:27:25.222 --> 00:27:26.930
So I went and I hired
a property manager.

00:27:26.930 --> 00:27:27.960
All right, great!

00:27:27.960 --> 00:27:29.230
Property manager screwed me.

00:27:29.230 --> 00:27:30.530
Hired another property manager.

00:27:30.530 --> 00:27:32.050
Property manager screwed me.

00:27:32.050 --> 00:27:33.330
Hired another one.

00:27:33.330 --> 00:27:36.585
And it was this dirty
trail of tears for me.

00:27:36.585 --> 00:27:41.220
And ultimately-- so you have
to know, a passive investment,

00:27:41.220 --> 00:27:44.224
you're not necessarily-- when
you've got these property

00:27:44.224 --> 00:27:46.140
managers, you want to
know how to screen them.

00:27:46.140 --> 00:27:47.130
You want to know
what to look for.

00:27:47.130 --> 00:27:49.213
And you want to make sure
they're doing their job.

00:27:49.213 --> 00:27:51.730
So there is the active part
of the passive investment.

00:27:51.730 --> 00:27:54.020
But in the end, again,
professional property managers

00:27:54.020 --> 00:27:55.020
are going to do the job.

00:27:55.020 --> 00:27:56.686
They're going to take
care of the asset.

00:27:56.686 --> 00:27:58.890
And they may even help
you find additional deals.

00:28:01.710 --> 00:28:02.550
BRANDON: All right.

00:28:02.550 --> 00:28:03.815
Step number seven.

00:28:03.815 --> 00:28:05.981
We're going to close this
thing up here in a minute.

00:28:05.981 --> 00:28:08.000
And that is planning
your exit strategy.

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:10.690
We talked about, earlier,
the map, driving from Seattle

00:28:10.690 --> 00:28:12.090
all the way down to Mexico City.

00:28:12.090 --> 00:28:13.820
You have to know
where Mexico City's at

00:28:13.820 --> 00:28:14.736
in order to get there.

00:28:14.736 --> 00:28:16.950
So you have to know where
your destination is.

00:28:16.950 --> 00:28:19.230
You may change throughout your
life where that destination is,

00:28:19.230 --> 00:28:20.880
but it's still important
to kind of plan for that.

00:28:20.880 --> 00:28:22.505
So we're going to
talk about just a few

00:28:22.505 --> 00:28:24.027
of the more common
exit strategies

00:28:24.027 --> 00:28:25.985
a person might have in
their investment career.

00:28:25.985 --> 00:28:28.470
So the first one would be
holding onto a property

00:28:28.470 --> 00:28:29.370
forever.

00:28:29.370 --> 00:28:31.826
What I mean by that is
indefinitely, right?

00:28:31.826 --> 00:28:33.700
So you might buy a bunch
of rental properties

00:28:33.700 --> 00:28:35.455
with no real plan
to get rid of them.

00:28:35.455 --> 00:28:39.040
And that's probably OK, as long
as you do your asset protection

00:28:39.040 --> 00:28:41.006
well, so when you
die your kids will

00:28:41.006 --> 00:28:42.130
get the property correctly.

00:28:42.130 --> 00:28:43.805
So there are people
who do hold forever,

00:28:43.805 --> 00:28:47.116
and that is a valid
exit strategy.

00:28:47.116 --> 00:28:48.240
JOSH: Sell it and cash out.

00:28:48.240 --> 00:28:50.230
So you buy a property.

00:28:50.230 --> 00:28:50.730
You sell it.

00:28:50.730 --> 00:28:51.890
Maybe you're flipping house.

00:28:51.890 --> 00:28:52.973
So you buy it, short term.

