00:38:48.410 --> 00:38:51.540
AUDIENCE: You had mentioned
that for commercial real estate,

00:38:51.540 --> 00:38:56.270
one strategy is to get 10 people
together and buy [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:56.270 --> 00:39:00.565
Are there smart ways of doing
that for smaller properties?

00:39:00.565 --> 00:39:04.030
So, for example, if I want
to buy a million dollar home,

00:39:04.030 --> 00:39:06.505
but I only have a
hundred thousand,

00:39:06.505 --> 00:39:11.455
are there resources where I
can find nine other people?

00:39:11.455 --> 00:39:13.930
I don't have nine friends or
nine people who I can trust.

00:39:13.930 --> 00:39:18.920
Are there safe ways to kind of
go in on real estate that way?

00:39:18.920 --> 00:39:19.690
BRANDON: Sure.

00:39:19.690 --> 00:39:21.190
I mean, there's a
few ways to do it.

00:39:21.190 --> 00:39:23.770
One of, I think, the best
ways that we talked about

00:39:23.770 --> 00:39:24.972
is networking, right?

00:39:24.972 --> 00:39:26.430
So if you go to a
real estate club,

00:39:26.430 --> 00:39:28.250
every major city has
real estate clubs,

00:39:28.250 --> 00:39:30.625
and some you have to be really
careful about, because all

00:39:30.625 --> 00:39:33.680
they are is just pitch-fest,
and buy this product.

00:39:33.680 --> 00:39:36.130
But if you can find a
good-- even at the bad ones,

00:39:36.130 --> 00:39:37.020
I mean if you can
find people who

00:39:37.020 --> 00:39:38.645
are interested in
doing deals together,

00:39:38.645 --> 00:39:39.951
they're all one mind, right?

00:39:39.951 --> 00:39:41.200
We want to buy deals together.

00:39:41.200 --> 00:39:42.104
So that's a good way.

00:39:42.104 --> 00:39:43.020
There is crowdfunding.

00:39:43.020 --> 00:39:45.159
It's kind of a new, it's
been coming out lately.

00:39:45.159 --> 00:39:47.200
It's like Kickstarter,
right, but for real estate

00:39:47.200 --> 00:39:47.650
investments.

00:39:47.650 --> 00:39:49.720
People pool their money-- you
don't even know who they are,

00:39:49.720 --> 00:39:51.720
just lots of people are
throwing their money in.

00:39:51.720 --> 00:39:54.582
That's kind of a new-- exciting
new twist on the real estate

00:39:54.582 --> 00:39:55.290
investment world.

00:39:55.290 --> 00:39:57.498
And we didn't really get a
chance to talk about a lot

00:39:57.498 --> 00:40:00.070
today, because personally I've
never invested in one of them.

00:40:00.070 --> 00:40:02.860
But that is a way
to do it as well.

00:40:02.860 --> 00:40:04.830
I would never go and
put up an advertisement

00:40:04.830 --> 00:40:07.413
in the newspaper that says, hey,
I'm looking for five partners

00:40:07.413 --> 00:40:08.480
to go and buy a property.

00:40:08.480 --> 00:40:10.146
That just seems like
you're calling down

00:40:10.146 --> 00:40:12.080
trouble from the
government on-- there's

00:40:12.080 --> 00:40:14.202
a lot of interesting
laws and stuff

00:40:14.202 --> 00:40:16.410
you have to deal when you
get into that so I wouldn't

00:40:16.410 --> 00:40:17.260
publicly do it.

00:40:17.260 --> 00:40:19.080
JOSH: So, really quick
to extend on that.

00:40:19.080 --> 00:40:21.230
So the SEC.

00:40:21.230 --> 00:40:24.330
The SEC is, has--

00:40:24.330 --> 00:40:25.604
MALE SPEAKER: Microphone!

00:40:25.604 --> 00:40:26.270
JOSH: Oh, sorry.

00:40:26.270 --> 00:40:26.770
Thank you.

00:40:26.770 --> 00:40:27.490
Thank you.

00:40:27.490 --> 00:40:28.480
Sorry.

00:40:28.480 --> 00:40:31.350
So the SEC has a lot
of rules about what

00:40:31.350 --> 00:40:34.160
you can do with raising money
for-- whether it be a company

00:40:34.160 --> 00:40:36.930
or for real estate, public
offerings, things like that.

00:40:36.930 --> 00:40:38.930
I'm not going to even try
and explain any of it.

00:40:38.930 --> 00:40:40.110
I'm not a lawyer.

00:40:40.110 --> 00:40:41.160
Don't pretend to be.

00:40:41.160 --> 00:40:44.580
But when you go in and
bring people together,

00:40:44.580 --> 00:40:46.810
you really need your
real estate attorney

00:40:46.810 --> 00:40:49.110
to make sure that
you're doing it kosher.

00:40:49.110 --> 00:40:51.620
If it's you and your brother,
and your five closest

00:40:51.620 --> 00:40:52.740
friends, fine.

00:40:52.740 --> 00:40:54.960
But once you start kind of
dealing with people that

00:40:54.960 --> 00:40:58.320
are outside of your-- even
people in your circle--

00:40:58.320 --> 00:41:00.250
you want to talk to a
lawyer and structure it,

00:41:00.250 --> 00:41:02.930
because there's a lot of
intricacies with the law.

00:41:02.930 --> 00:41:05.310
So you want to make sure
you're doing it the right way.

00:41:05.310 --> 00:41:07.580
And on the crowdfunding
thing, really quickly.

00:41:07.580 --> 00:41:12.360
So a lot of these sites have
come out of the JOBS Act, where

00:41:12.360 --> 00:41:16.930
funding is kind of-- I guess
the SEC's kind of loosened

00:41:16.930 --> 00:41:18.150
up about what's allowed.

00:41:18.150 --> 00:41:19.700
But it's not like
Kickstarter, right?

00:41:19.700 --> 00:41:23.520
Kickstarter, you go and
you're donating cash, right?

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:25.020
You're donating
money for a project,

00:41:25.020 --> 00:41:27.374
and you get a prize in
return for that donation.

00:41:27.374 --> 00:41:28.790
With crowdfunding,
you're actually

00:41:28.790 --> 00:41:29.940
investing in the property.

00:41:29.940 --> 00:41:32.420
So the government is
pretty hardcore in their--

00:41:32.420 --> 00:41:36.970
this is a very nascent
way to finance property.

00:41:36.970 --> 00:41:41.470
And so, personally, I would
not get into a deal that way.

00:41:41.470 --> 00:41:42.970
I want to watch and
see what's going

00:41:42.970 --> 00:41:46.010
to happen before I
would jump into that.

00:41:46.010 --> 00:41:47.420
So, anyone else?

00:41:47.420 --> 00:41:48.920
AUDIENCE: Was
wondering if you could

00:41:48.920 --> 00:41:52.824
say a bit more about property
management [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:52.824 --> 00:41:58.000
what to watch out for, what
can go wrong, [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:00.500
JOSH: All right, so the question
was on property management,

00:42:00.500 --> 00:42:03.010
how to find them,
what to look for.

00:42:03.010 --> 00:42:05.570
This is not a shameless
plug, but we-- years ago,

00:42:05.570 --> 00:42:08.160
when I was dealing with all
the chaos of my own property

00:42:08.160 --> 00:42:11.770
management, I put together
a list of questions.

00:42:11.770 --> 00:42:14.810
And it was, I don't
remember them now

00:42:14.810 --> 00:42:17.980
off the top of my
head, but we can

00:42:17.980 --> 00:42:19.780
find a way to get
it to you guys.

00:42:19.780 --> 00:42:23.610
But ultimately,
you want to know do

00:42:23.610 --> 00:42:26.260
you want a property manager who
manages their own properties?

00:42:26.260 --> 00:42:27.530
Are they competing?

00:42:27.530 --> 00:42:29.180
Are they going to take
tenants and put their tenants

00:42:29.180 --> 00:42:30.550
in their own properties
before they put them

00:42:30.550 --> 00:42:31.560
in your properties.

00:42:31.560 --> 00:42:33.549
So you want to interview them.

00:42:33.549 --> 00:42:34.340
What's their style?

00:42:34.340 --> 00:42:35.798
What they do with
tenant screening?

00:42:35.798 --> 00:42:38.050
How careful are they
in looking for tenants?

00:42:38.050 --> 00:42:39.780
What's their policy
on late rents?

00:42:39.780 --> 00:42:42.720
What's their policy
on contractors?

00:42:42.720 --> 00:42:45.820
How do they manage
broken toilets?

00:42:45.820 --> 00:42:48.670
You need to-- there's
a thousand questions

00:42:48.670 --> 00:42:50.130
that we can go through.

00:42:50.130 --> 00:42:53.379
Ultimately, the key is not
just picking the first property

00:42:53.379 --> 00:42:54.420
manager that's out there.

00:42:54.420 --> 00:42:56.135
You literally want
to go out there.

00:42:56.135 --> 00:42:57.970
And the same goes for real
estate agents, and pretty

00:42:57.970 --> 00:43:00.386
much anybody else that you're
dealing with in real estate.

00:43:00.386 --> 00:43:02.590
You want to interview
multiple people,

00:43:02.590 --> 00:43:05.210
and you want to find out
what their policies are.

00:43:05.210 --> 00:43:06.310
Ask the same questions.

00:43:06.310 --> 00:43:09.384
Find out what their
answers are, and rinse

00:43:09.384 --> 00:43:10.800
and repeat until
you find somebody

00:43:10.800 --> 00:43:12.670
who fits the bill that
you're looking for.

00:43:12.670 --> 00:43:14.714
I don't know if that
answers it, but.

00:43:14.714 --> 00:43:17.130
BRANDON: I do want to throw
in one more suggestion, is get

00:43:17.130 --> 00:43:19.460
recommendations from other
real estate investors.

00:43:19.460 --> 00:43:21.514
I mean, like, anybody you
can find who does this.

00:43:21.514 --> 00:43:22.930
And it's fairly
easy to find them,

00:43:22.930 --> 00:43:24.830
like I said, at the real
estate clubs or whatever.

00:43:24.830 --> 00:43:25.810
Get recommendations.

00:43:25.810 --> 00:43:27.851
The hands-down the best
way to know if somebody's

00:43:27.851 --> 00:43:30.827
going to be good is to
know if they've been good.

00:43:30.827 --> 00:43:32.160
The best way is just reputation.

00:43:32.160 --> 00:43:34.660
What have they been to other
people that are similar to you?

00:43:34.660 --> 00:43:37.450
So if you can find that
question out, get referrals.

00:43:37.450 --> 00:43:39.917
If you ask me, there's five
property managers in my town--

00:43:39.917 --> 00:43:42.000
companies in my town--
I'll tell you four of them,

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:43.070
do not go near.

00:43:43.070 --> 00:43:44.460
There's one that I would use.

00:43:44.460 --> 00:43:46.270
I don't use them yet, but
I will use them someday.

00:43:46.270 --> 00:43:47.811
But the other four,
I won't use them.

00:43:47.811 --> 00:43:50.228
I'm happy to tell you that,
because I want you to succeed.

00:43:50.228 --> 00:43:52.144
Real estate investors
love to help each other.

00:43:52.144 --> 00:43:54.660
It's not that competitive of
a business as you might think

00:43:54.660 --> 00:43:56.451
Everyone I've ever
known has been open very

00:43:56.451 --> 00:43:59.170
open to share and to say,
here, do this, don't do this.

00:43:59.170 --> 00:44:02.390
JOSH: And actually, on that
subject of competition,

00:44:02.390 --> 00:44:04.850
a lot of new investors will
come out and say, oh, well,

00:44:04.850 --> 00:44:06.558
you know, I'm competing--
it kind of goes

00:44:06.558 --> 00:44:09.214
to the question about all these
investors jumping on deals.

00:44:09.214 --> 00:44:10.630
I'm competing with
all these guys.

00:44:10.630 --> 00:44:13.320
Well, people who've been
investing for more than one

00:44:13.320 --> 00:44:16.220
or two deals typically
look at their competitors

00:44:16.220 --> 00:44:17.840
as collaborators.

00:44:17.840 --> 00:44:20.685
You may say, hey Brandon--
you may go and find a deal.

00:44:20.685 --> 00:44:22.540
You may do marketing,
send out letters

00:44:22.540 --> 00:44:24.670
to people who are in
distressed situations,

00:44:24.670 --> 00:44:26.990
and come up with
people, somebody

00:44:26.990 --> 00:44:29.780
who's mom just died and needs
to get rid of her property.

00:44:29.780 --> 00:44:30.530
And you know what?

00:44:30.530 --> 00:44:31.650
You don't have
cash at this point,

00:44:31.650 --> 00:44:33.740
because you just bought
another property, right?

00:44:33.740 --> 00:44:36.050
So three days later, after
you bought a property,

00:44:36.050 --> 00:44:37.800
a phenomenal deal comes in.

00:44:37.800 --> 00:44:40.500
Well, you know Brandon's looking
for a similar-type property.

00:44:40.500 --> 00:44:43.280
Well, I'm going to work with
Brandon to get the deal done.

00:44:43.280 --> 00:44:45.910
I'm not going to make as much
as I might have made otherwise.

00:44:45.910 --> 00:44:47.610
But at least I can
make some money,

00:44:47.610 --> 00:44:49.520
or at least I can
give it over to him.

00:44:49.520 --> 00:44:51.480
He can make some money,
and, you know, payback,

00:44:51.480 --> 00:44:52.440
scratchy-scratchy.

00:44:52.440 --> 00:44:55.200
So investors like
to work together.

00:44:55.200 --> 00:44:57.330
And if you can
collaborate and not

00:44:57.330 --> 00:45:00.670
think of the other investors
in your area as competitors,

00:45:00.670 --> 00:45:03.280
you're going to do way
better than the folks who do

00:45:03.280 --> 00:45:05.106
think that way.

