MALE SPEAKER: Could you
repeat the question?

00:47:58.650 --> 00:48:00.816
BRANDON: Yeah, I'll repeat
that question real quick.

00:48:00.816 --> 00:48:03.719
He basically said, his
first property he bought,

00:48:03.719 --> 00:48:04.760
he lived in the property.

00:48:04.760 --> 00:48:06.769
Then he moved and
bought another house.

00:48:06.769 --> 00:48:08.060
So he rented the first one out.

00:48:08.060 --> 00:48:08.820
Then he did that again.

00:48:08.820 --> 00:48:10.270
And you can do that a few times.

00:48:10.270 --> 00:48:11.750
But every time you
do it, when you

00:48:11.750 --> 00:48:13.580
go to a bank to
try to get a loan,

00:48:13.580 --> 00:48:16.895
they're going to only count
part of the income that comes in

00:48:16.895 --> 00:48:17.520
towards income.

00:48:17.520 --> 00:48:19.061
The bank is going
to say, well, we're

00:48:19.061 --> 00:48:21.750
only to give you 75%
of what comes in.

00:48:21.750 --> 00:48:23.445
So the more you buy,
the harder it gets.

00:48:23.445 --> 00:48:25.570
And this is one of the
really frustrating questions

00:48:25.570 --> 00:48:27.250
a lot of investors
have, is pretty soon,

00:48:27.250 --> 00:48:29.234
the banks start saying
no, very quickly.

00:48:29.234 --> 00:48:31.400
I mean, I got to, I think--
and there's also limits.

00:48:31.400 --> 00:48:34.100
Like, a lot of banks say you
cannot have more than four.

00:48:34.100 --> 00:48:35.610
We're going to cap you at four.

00:48:35.610 --> 00:48:37.506
And so these two
problems, right, I

00:48:37.506 --> 00:48:39.130
mean like they're
both kind of related.

00:48:39.130 --> 00:48:40.870
Banks will just
have a flat ceiling.

00:48:40.870 --> 00:48:42.120
You can't have more than four.

00:48:42.120 --> 00:48:43.897
Or your debt to
income it's called,

00:48:43.897 --> 00:48:45.480
which is getting a
little complicated,

00:48:45.480 --> 00:48:46.950
but your ratios don't work out.

00:48:46.950 --> 00:48:48.360
Sorry, you're denied.

00:48:48.360 --> 00:48:50.769
What I say is,
for somebody who's

00:48:50.769 --> 00:48:53.227
got a little bit of creativity,
and you can work around it.

00:48:53.227 --> 00:48:54.950
But my favorite
method of doing this--

00:48:54.950 --> 00:48:56.700
this is what I've done
a number of times--

00:48:56.700 --> 00:48:57.940
is I work with a partner.

00:48:57.940 --> 00:48:58.981
We talked about partners.

00:48:58.981 --> 00:48:59.940
This is why I do it.

00:48:59.940 --> 00:49:01.690
So what I'll do is
I'll find a partner who

00:49:01.690 --> 00:49:04.525
has great credit, great income,
he can qualify for a loan.

00:49:04.525 --> 00:49:05.900
He can go into a
bank, he doesn't

00:49:05.900 --> 00:49:07.320
own any rental property, really.

00:49:07.320 --> 00:49:10.285
But he likes what I do, and
he's got what I don't have,

00:49:10.285 --> 00:49:11.910
is the ability to
get another mortgage.

00:49:11.910 --> 00:49:14.300
We say, OK, let's
do this together.

00:49:14.300 --> 00:49:16.350
We'll use your
income and credit.

00:49:16.350 --> 00:49:18.306
I'll find a deal, put
the thing together,

00:49:18.306 --> 00:49:20.264
and we'll just split
everything 50/50 later on.

00:49:20.264 --> 00:49:21.240
Doesn't have to be 50/50.

00:49:21.240 --> 00:49:22.948
You can get what you
need, and negotiate.

00:49:22.948 --> 00:49:25.146
But what that
enables is, the bank

00:49:25.146 --> 00:49:26.270
doesn't look at me anymore.

00:49:26.270 --> 00:49:27.282
They're looking at him.

00:49:27.282 --> 00:49:29.240
Even though I'm still on
title on the property,

00:49:29.240 --> 00:49:31.323
it's just a nice way to
use somebody else's income

00:49:31.323 --> 00:49:32.454
and work together.

00:49:32.454 --> 00:49:34.370
You have to find the
right partner to do that,

00:49:34.370 --> 00:49:35.490
but that's one way.

00:49:35.490 --> 00:49:37.899
Otherwise we can talk
about portfolio loans.

00:49:37.899 --> 00:49:39.940
Portfolio loans are how
a lot of investors do it.

00:49:39.940 --> 00:49:41.990
I got a portfolio
lender right now, just

00:49:41.990 --> 00:49:44.129
a local bank in my area.

00:49:44.129 --> 00:49:45.920
And they've flat-out
told me like, oh yeah,

00:49:45.920 --> 00:49:47.110
you can get as many
loans as you want.

00:49:47.110 --> 00:49:47.610
It's OK.

00:49:47.610 --> 00:49:50.270
We don't have a max, because
we keep them in-house.

00:49:50.270 --> 00:49:53.200
We're not selling them up to
big Fannie Mae Freddie Mac

00:49:53.200 --> 00:49:55.650
institutions that cap
you at a certain number.

00:49:55.650 --> 00:49:57.529
As long as the deal
looks OK, we're

00:49:57.529 --> 00:49:59.445
going to keep doing them
for you all day long.

00:49:59.445 --> 00:50:02.410
JOSH: Yeah and the
portfolio lenders

00:50:02.410 --> 00:50:04.060
is-- they're going
to look at the deal.

00:50:04.060 --> 00:50:04.870
They're going to
look at the person,

00:50:04.870 --> 00:50:05.550
they're going to
look at the deal,

00:50:05.550 --> 00:50:06.980
they're going to look
at the experience.

00:50:06.980 --> 00:50:08.220
They're going to say,
you know what, Brandon,

00:50:08.220 --> 00:50:09.939
you've been doing
this for awhile.

00:50:09.939 --> 00:50:10.730
I like the numbers.

00:50:10.730 --> 00:50:12.090
You're paying on time.

00:50:12.090 --> 00:50:14.110
This next property that
you've got looks great.

00:50:14.110 --> 00:50:14.610
Great.

00:50:14.610 --> 00:50:15.359
Here's your money.

00:50:15.359 --> 00:50:21.240
I mean you'll text your
agent and pick up a deal,

00:50:21.240 --> 00:50:25.350
and then you basically send
it over, e-mail it over,

00:50:25.350 --> 00:50:27.350
and so next thing you
know you've got the money.

00:50:27.350 --> 00:50:31.280
I mean, it really becomes that
easy as you get the experience

00:50:31.280 --> 00:50:33.950
if you're working with somebody
who sees what you're doing,

00:50:33.950 --> 00:50:37.180
sees that-- but it's not going
to happen when you first start.

00:50:37.180 --> 00:50:39.750
But you want to definitely
search out portfolio lenders.

00:50:39.750 --> 00:50:42.050
They're definitely going
to be a great asset.

00:50:42.050 --> 00:50:43.310
BRANDON: And to find them,
in case you're wondering,

00:50:43.310 --> 00:50:44.600
if anybody wants to know
how to find portfolio

00:50:44.600 --> 00:50:46.315
lenders-- easiest
way, pick up the phone

00:50:46.315 --> 00:50:47.130
and just start calling.

00:50:47.130 --> 00:50:48.250
I mean I would
estimate-- I don't

00:50:48.250 --> 00:50:49.240
know with these
numbers, numbers,

00:50:49.240 --> 00:50:50.930
but I'd estimate 20%
to 30% of all banks

00:50:50.930 --> 00:50:52.264
out there are portfolio lenders.

00:50:52.264 --> 00:50:53.638
That might be
high, I don't know.

00:50:53.638 --> 00:50:55.510
But if you call enough,
like, we interviewed

00:50:55.510 --> 00:50:57.840
a guy a couple weeks ago,
he said he called 50 people

00:50:57.840 --> 00:50:59.382
and he got one or
two of them to say,

00:50:59.382 --> 00:51:00.673
yeah we'll do a loan like that.

00:51:00.673 --> 00:51:01.790
We're portfolio lenders.

00:51:01.790 --> 00:51:03.300
Not all of them
use that language.

00:51:03.300 --> 00:51:04.841
They might not say
portfolio lenders.

00:51:04.841 --> 00:51:07.454
But the idea is, do you
keep your loans in-house,

00:51:07.454 --> 00:51:09.370
or do you sell them to
Fannie Mae Freddie Mac.

00:51:09.370 --> 00:51:11.078
That's what we define
a portfolio lender.

00:51:11.078 --> 00:51:12.480
So just call on all of them.

00:51:12.480 --> 00:51:13.975
Steer clear of the big banks.

00:51:13.975 --> 00:51:16.820
I mean anything that's national
or goes to different states,

00:51:16.820 --> 00:51:18.820
those ones aren't going
to be portfolio lenders.

00:51:18.820 --> 00:51:21.650
It's the small community banks,
the credit unions, the ones

00:51:21.650 --> 00:51:24.090
that you kind of see
in your neighborhood.

00:51:24.090 --> 00:51:26.120
They got a dozen,
two dozen branches.

00:51:26.120 --> 00:51:28.344
Those are the ones
you want to focus on.

00:51:28.344 --> 00:51:29.385
JOSH: You had a question.

00:51:29.385 --> 00:51:30.301
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

